## The First Formal Artifact of the Authorization Package

Day 42 closed out the Prepare step and Day 43 opens the Categorize step — the first of the six formal steps in the NIST RMF that produce the artifacts an Authorizing Official will review before making the risk acceptance decision. The Categorize step has two tasks: Task C-1 asks for a formal system description, and Task C-2 asks for the security categorization. Together they produce the foundational documentation that drives everything else in the authorization package.

Task C-1 might seem like repetition — I have been describing OpenMRS in various ways since Day 17. But the system description in the System Security Plan has a specific purpose and a specific audience that distinguishes it from the architecture work, the asset inventory, the mission documentation, and the registration record. The SSP system description is written for a reader who needs to understand the system well enough to evaluate whether the security controls are appropriate — an assessor, an Authorizing Official, or a future ISSO inheriting the program. It needs to be precise, complete, and self-contained.

Today I worked through producing the formal Task C-1 system description as it would appear in the System Security Plan for OpenMRS at MyClinic.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-18 — the guide for developing System Security Plans — provides specific guidance on what the system description section must include: system name, system categorization, system owner, operational status, system type, general description of function, information types, operational environment, system interconnections, and laws and regulations applicable to the system.

The formal system description synthesizes work from across the entire Prepare step into a single reference section. Rather than producing another high-level overview, I focused today on writing the description at the level of precision that an assessor would actually need — specific enough to evaluate control applicability, complete enough to understand the full operational picture.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most clearly today is the difference between a system description written for *communication* and one written for *assessment*.

A communication-oriented system description — the kind that appears in a project proposal or an executive briefing — focuses on what the system does and why it matters. It uses accessible language, avoids jargon, and leads with business value.

An assessment-oriented system description — the kind that belongs in a System Security Plan — focuses on what the system *is* at a technical and operational level in enough detail that a security assessor can determine whether the documented controls are appropriate and complete. It needs to answer: what components are in scope? What data flows through them? Who has access? How do external connections work? What is the operational environment?

Both types are legitimate and useful — but they serve different purposes and different audiences. The SSP system description I produced today is written for the assessor, not the executive briefing. That shift in audience changes what information is included and at what level of detail.

