### 6. Information Types and Data Flows

**Information Types Handled (from Task P-12 analysis):**

| Information Type | Sensitivity | Primary Location |
|---|---|---|
| Patient identity and demographics | High (PHI) | RDS database |
| Clinical health records | High (PHI) | RDS database |
| Laboratory and diagnostic results | High (PHI) | RDS database |
| User account and access control data | Moderate-High | RDS database |
| Application audit logs | High (integrity critical) | CloudWatch Logs; RDS |
| Billing and financial information | High (PHI when combined) | RDS database |
| System configuration data | Moderate-High (integrity critical) | EC2 filesystem; RDS |
| Encrypted backup data | High | S3 |

**Primary Data Flows:**

*User to Application:*
Clinical and administrative staff → HTTPS (TLS 1.2+) → AWS WAF → EC2 OpenMRS Application Server
All user interaction with patient data flows through this path. Authentication occurs at the application layer.

*Application to Database:*
EC2 Application Server → MySQL over TLS → RDS Private Subnet
All patient data reads and writes flow through this internal path. Connection restricted by security group to application server security group membership.

*Application to Backup Storage:*
EC2/RDS → Encrypted export → S3 Backup Bucket (private; KMS encrypted)
Nightly automated backup process. No external access to backup data.

*Laboratory Integration:*
Laboratory Information System → REST API over HTTPS → EC2 OpenMRS Application Server
Laboratory results transmitted from external laboratory provider. Authenticated via API key; TLS enforced. Governed by BAA and ISA.

*Application to Logging:*
EC2 OpenMRS Application → CloudWatch Logs Agent → CloudWatch Log Group
Audit log events generated by OpenMRS application (patient record access, modifications, authentication events) shipped to CloudWatch in near-real-time.

*AWS Service Logging:*
All AWS API calls across account → CloudTrail → Protected S3 bucket (separate from backup bucket)

