## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While working through the level of precision required for a formal system description today, I came across post-incident analysis from the **2015 Excellus BlueCross BlueShield breach** — which I covered briefly on Day 15, but want to revisit through the documentation lens.

Excellus was breached in December 2013. The breach was not discovered until August 2015 — nearly 20 months later. During the HHS OCR investigation that followed, one of the findings concerned the adequacy of Excellus's documentation of its systems and data flows. The OCR investigation found gaps in Excellus's ability to demonstrate that it had conducted a thorough, accurate, and organization-wide risk analysis — in part because the system inventory and documentation were not sufficient to establish a complete picture of where ePHI resided and how it was protected.

The settlement reached $5.1 million. Approximately 10 million individuals were affected.

The Excellus case illustrates why Task C-1 is not administrative overhead. An accurate, maintained system description is part of the evidentiary foundation that demonstrates a reasonable and appropriate security program. When OCR investigates a breach and asks "did you know what systems you had and how they were protected?" — the system description in the SSP is part of the answer. An organization that cannot produce complete, accurate documentation of its systems has a harder time demonstrating that it implemented reasonable and appropriate safeguards, regardless of what controls were actually in place.

