## What I Am Still Thinking About

Working through the system description today, one detail stood out that I want to address more carefully: the version number field.

I documented the OpenMRS version as "OpenMRS Platform 2.x with Reference Application — version number to be confirmed at time of assessment." In a real authorization package, the specific version number matters — it determines which CVEs apply to the running system and whether the assessment team can verify that the software is current and patched.

For the SSP to be truly accurate, the version number needs to be pinned to the specific release in production. This creates a maintenance challenge: every time OpenMRS is updated, the SSP needs to be updated to reflect the new version. That seems like overhead, but it is exactly the kind of change management discipline that keeps the documentation accurate and the security program continuously reflecting the actual system state.

The version management process — tracking what is running, confirming it is current, updating documentation when it changes — is a small but important operational discipline that I want to build explicitly into the change management process developed for Day 41's requirements allocation discussion.

